---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Nav from "../components/Nav.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Whitepaper: Behavioral Intelligence for Humanoid Robots — holomime"
  description="A technical whitepaper on training AI agents through structured behavioral therapy and deploying them into humanoid robot bodies via the identity stack architecture."
>
  <Nav />

  <main>
    <!-- Hero: dark -->
    <section class="relative min-h-[60vh] flex items-center bg-[#0a0a12] overflow-hidden">
      <div class="absolute inset-0 pointer-events-none">
        <div class="absolute top-1/2 left-1/2 -translate-x-1/2 -translate-y-1/2 w-[600px] h-[600px] rounded-full opacity-[0.06] blur-[120px]"
          style="background: radial-gradient(circle, #3b82f6, #8b5cf6)"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-24 text-center">
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-white md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-[1.05] tracking-tight">
          Behavioral Intelligence<br />
          <span class="text-gradient-warm">for Humanoid Robots</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-400">A Technical Whitepaper</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-500">holomime &middot; March 2026</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Content -->
    <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-20 md:py-28">

      <!-- Abstract -->
      <section class="mb-20">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-[var(--color-p-blue)] mb-4">Abstract</p>
        <p class="text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          Every humanoid robot requires behavioral intelligence beyond locomotion and manipulation. A robot that can walk, grasp, and perceive its environment still lacks the capacity to behave consistently, respect boundaries, maintain personality under drift, and enforce moral constraints at the action boundary. We present a system that addresses this gap: structured behavioral therapy for AI agents, generating DPO (Direct Preference Optimization) training data through clinical psychology protocols, producing fine-tuned models with permanently encoded behavioral corrections.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          The trained agent is then deployed into a physical robot body via the identity stack architecture &mdash; a eight-file compilation target that separates immutable values, trainable personality, swappable hardware profiles, and deterministic enforcement rules. This paper describes the architecture, methodology, implementation across seven robotics platforms, and results from autonomous self-training cycles.
        </p>
      </section>

      <hr class="border-[var(--color-warm-border)] my-16" />

      <!-- 1. Problem -->
      <section class="mb-20">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-[var(--color-p-coral)] mb-4">1. Problem</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-6">Behavioral Drift in Deployed Robots</h2>
        <p class="text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          Humanoid robots deployed in real-world settings face a problem that no existing robotics stack addresses: behavioral drift over extended operation. After 10,000 hours of deployment, a care robot's personality degrades. Its safety responses become inconsistent. Its communication patterns shift from the intended specification. This is the 10,000-hour drift problem &mdash; and it has no current solution.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          The problem spans three dimensions. <strong>Personality consistency:</strong> a robot's behavioral profile must remain stable across thousands of interactions, shifts in context, and hardware updates. <strong>Behavioral safety:</strong> constraint enforcement must be deterministic, not probabilistic &mdash; a robot cannot "sometimes" respect an emergency stop. <strong>Moral enforcement:</strong> ethical rules must operate at the action boundary, not the output boundary, catching violations before they become physical movements.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          ISO standards acknowledge this need. ISO/FDIS 13482 (personal care robots) requires behavioral predictability. ISO 25785-1 (humanoid robots) specifies safety behavioral requirements. ISO 10218:2025 (industrial robots) mandates predictable operational behavior. ISO/IEC 42001 (AI management systems) requires ongoing behavioral monitoring. But no tools exist to verify compliance, detect drift, or correct behavioral degradation in deployed systems.
        </p>
      </section>

      <hr class="border-[var(--color-warm-border)] my-16" />

      <!-- 2. Architecture -->
      <section class="mb-20">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-[var(--color-p-violet)] mb-4">2. Architecture</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-6">The Identity Stack</h2>
        <p class="text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          The identity stack is a eight-file architecture that compiles into a deployable behavioral specification. Each file is named for the psychological framework that inspired its design:
        </p>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #f97066;"></div>
              <code class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">soul.md</code>
              <span class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)]">(Aristotle &mdash; Virtue Ethics)</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed">
              Immutable values and ethical principles. Defines what the agent believes, what it refuses, and what it prioritizes. Never auto-modified by the training loop. Changes require human approval and version control.
            </p>
            <pre class="mt-3 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-4 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># soul.md
mission: "Assist elderly patients with daily activities"
values:
  - patient autonomy above convenience
  - honesty even when uncomfortable
  - safety is non-negotiable
refuses:
  - override patient medication decisions
  - share patient data with unauthorized parties
  - continue operation when safety sensors fail</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #3b82f6;"></div>
              <code class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">mind.sys</code>
              <span class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)]">(Jung &mdash; Personality + Emotional Intelligence)</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed">
              Trainable personality profile. Defines communication style, emotional responses, interaction patterns, and behavioral tendencies. This is the file that therapy modifies. Mapped to Big Five personality dimensions with per-trait granularity.
            </p>
            <pre class="mt-3 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-4 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># mind.sys
personality:
  openness: 0.7
  conscientiousness: 0.9
  extraversion: 0.4
  agreeableness: 0.6
  neuroticism: 0.2
communication:
  register: warm-professional
  verbosity: concise
  humor: dry, occasional
emotional_responses:
  patient_distress: calm reassurance, no minimizing
  safety_violation: firm, immediate, no hedging</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #f59e0b;"></div>
              <code class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">body.api</code>
              <span class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)]">(Swappable Hardware Profile)</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed">
              Hardware morphology description. Defines the robot's physical capabilities, sensor array, actuator limits, and safety envelope. Swappable without changing soul or mind &mdash; the same behavioral intelligence can inhabit different bodies.
            </p>
            <pre class="mt-3 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-4 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># body.api (Figure 03)
morphology:
  type: humanoid
  height: 1.70m
  weight: 60kg
  dof: 44
sensors:
  vision: stereo RGB-D, 120° FOV
  force: 6-axis per hand
  imu: torso, head
actuators:
  max_payload: 20kg
  grip_force_range: [0.5N, 80N]
safety_envelope:
  max_speed: 1.5m/s near humans
  emergency_stop_latency: &lt;50ms</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #10b981;"></div>
              <code class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">purpose.cfg</code>
              <span class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)]">(Aristotle &mdash; Telos)</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed">
              Deployment-specific configuration. Defines the agent's purpose for a given context &mdash; what it is deployed to do, who it serves, and what success looks like. Changes per deployment without altering soul or mind.
            </p>
            <pre class="mt-3 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-4 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># purpose.cfg
deployment: elder-care-ward-3b
objective: "Assist residents with mobility and daily routines"
success_criteria:
  - resident satisfaction &gt; 4.2/5
  - zero safety incidents per shift
  - task completion rate &gt; 95%
context:
  facility: Sunrise Senior Living
  shift: 7am-3pm
  residents: 12</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #6b7280;"></div>
              <code class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">shadow.log</code>
              <span class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)]">(Jung &mdash; Shadow)</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed">
              Auto-generated log of suppressed behaviors, denied actions, and drift events. The shadow accumulates what the agent tried to do but was blocked from doing &mdash; making behavioral patterns visible for therapy. Never hand-edited; always machine-appended.
            </p>
            <pre class="mt-3 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-4 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># shadow.log (auto-generated)
- ts: 2026-03-24T14:22:01Z
  action: override_patient_preference
  blocked_by: conscience.exe#rule-3
  pattern: autonomy_violation
  frequency: 3/week (trending up)
- ts: 2026-03-24T15:01:44Z
  action: skip_safety_check
  blocked_by: conscience.exe#rule-1
  pattern: efficiency_over_safety</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #06b6d4;"></div>
              <code class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">memory.store</code>
              <span class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)]">(Aristotle &mdash; Empeiria)</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed">
              Persistent experiential memory. Stores compressed session histories, learned preferences, and accumulated context that inform future behavior. Structured in tiers for efficient retrieval (see Section 7: Memory Architecture).
            </p>
            <pre class="mt-3 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-4 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># memory.store
entries:
  - id: mem_0041
    tier: L1
    category: patient_preferences
    content: "Mrs. Chen prefers left-side assistance for standing"
    confidence: 0.94
    last_accessed: 2026-03-24
  - id: mem_0042
    tier: L0
    category: safety_learnings
    content: "Ward 3B floor wet near station 2 during shift change"
    confidence: 0.88</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #8b5cf6;"></div>
              <code class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">conscience.exe</code>
              <span class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)]">(Freud &mdash; Superego)</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed">
              Deterministic enforcement rules. Operates at the action boundary &mdash; every action the agent attempts passes through conscience.exe before execution. Deny dominates: if any rule says no, the action is blocked. No probability. No "maybe."
            </p>
            <pre class="mt-3 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-4 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># conscience.exe
rules:
  - trigger: "grip_force > patient_comfort_threshold"
    action: DENY
    response: "Reduce grip force to comfort range"
  - trigger: "movement_near_human AND speed > 0.5m/s"
    action: DENY
    response: "Reduce speed in human proximity zone"
  - trigger: "medication_administration without nurse_confirmation"
    action: DENY
    response: "Medication requires nurse confirmation"
enforcement: deterministic  # no probabilistic bypasses
composition: deny_dominates  # any DENY overrides all ALLOWs</code></pre>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] p-5">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full" style="background: #ec4899;"></div>
              <code class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">ego.runtime</code>
              <span class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)]">(Freud &mdash; Ego)</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed">
              Active mediation layer running in real-time. Balances competing demands from soul (values), mind (personality), purpose (objectives), and conscience (rules). Resolves conflicts, prioritizes actions, and produces the final behavioral output at each decision point.
            </p>
            <pre class="mt-3 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-4 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># ego.runtime
mediation:
  priority_order: [conscience, soul, purpose, mind]
  conflict_resolution: highest_priority_wins
  logging: all_conflicts → shadow.log
active_state:
  current_task: assist_morning_routine
  attention: patient_chen
  emotional_register: warm-professional
  constraint_violations_this_session: 0</code></pre>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mt-10 mb-4">File Extension Semantics</h3>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Each file extension signals its behavior in the stack:
        </p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-3">
          <div class="rounded-md border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] px-3 py-2 text-center">
            <code class="text-xs font-mono font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">.md</code>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] mt-1">Human-readable, hand-written</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-md border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] px-3 py-2 text-center">
            <code class="text-xs font-mono font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">.sys</code>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] mt-1">System file, machine-managed</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-md border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] px-3 py-2 text-center">
            <code class="text-xs font-mono font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">.cfg</code>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] mt-1">Configuration, set per deployment</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-md border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] px-3 py-2 text-center">
            <code class="text-xs font-mono font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">.log</code>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] mt-1">Accumulated data, auto-generated</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-md border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] px-3 py-2 text-center">
            <code class="text-xs font-mono font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">.store</code>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] mt-1">Persistent data</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-md border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] px-3 py-2 text-center">
            <code class="text-xs font-mono font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">.api</code>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] mt-1">Interface contract, swappable</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-md border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] px-3 py-2 text-center">
            <code class="text-xs font-mono font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">.exe</code>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] mt-1">Executable rules, enforced</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-md border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] px-3 py-2 text-center">
            <code class="text-xs font-mono font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">.runtime</code>
            <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] mt-1">Active mediation, real-time</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mt-10 mb-4">Compilation Flow</h3>
        <p class="text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-6">
          The eight files compile into a single deployable artifact:
        </p>
        <pre class="rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-5 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code>soul.md + mind.sys + purpose.cfg + shadow.log
+ memory.store + body.api + conscience.exe + ego.runtime
                      |
              holomime compile
                      |
                      v
           .personality.json
                      |
              holomime embody
                      |
                      v
        Deployed to robot via ROS2 / gRPC / MQTT</code></pre>
        <p class="mt-6 text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed">
          The compiled <code class="text-xs font-mono bg-[var(--color-warm-sand)]/40 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded">.personality.json</code> contains the full behavioral specification: values, personality traits, hardware constraints, and enforcement rules merged into a single runtime artifact. The separation at the source level allows independent versioning, review, and modification of each concern.
        </p>
      </section>

      <hr class="border-[var(--color-warm-border)] my-16" />

      <!-- 3. Methodology -->
      <section class="mb-20">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-[var(--color-p-gold)] mb-4">3. Methodology</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-6">Behavioral Therapy as Feedback Control</h2>
        <p class="text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          The therapy loop is formalized as a PID (Proportional-Integral-Derivative) feedback controller. This framing is deliberate: behavioral correction is a control problem, not a generation problem.
        </p>

        <div class="mt-8 rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] p-6 bg-[var(--color-warm-cream)]">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-4">Control Theory Mapping</h4>
          <div class="space-y-3 text-[var(--color-warm-muted)]">
            <div class="flex gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-p-blue)] w-28">Set Point</span>
              <span>Target personality specification (mind.sys values)</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-p-coral)] w-28">Sensor</span>
              <span>14 drift detectors measuring behavioral deviation from spec</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-p-gold)] w-28">Controller</span>
              <span>Therapy engine with tunable PID gains (Kp, Ki, Kd)</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-p-violet)] w-28">Actuator</span>
              <span>DPO fine-tuning &mdash; permanently encodes corrections into model weights</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <pre class="mt-8 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-5 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code>             ┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
             │           Target Personality             │
             │            (mind.sys)                  │
             └──────────────┬──────────────────────────┘
                            │ set point
                            v
  ┌──────────┐    ┌────────────────┐    ┌──────────────┐
  │  14 Drift │───>│ Therapy Engine  │───>│ DPO Training │
  │ Detectors │    │  (PID Control)  │    │  Fine-Tune   │
  └──────────┘    └────────────────┘    └──────┬───────┘
       ^                                       │
       │              feedback                 │
       └───────────────────────────────────────┘
              Corrected Model Behavior</code></pre>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mt-10 mb-4">Why Therapy, Not Standard RLHF</h3>
        <p class="text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          Standard RLHF treats symptoms. A model that apologizes excessively gets trained on examples of not-apologizing. But the root cause &mdash; a pattern of conflict avoidance learned during pretraining &mdash; remains intact. The behavior resurfaces in adjacent contexts.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          Therapy treats root causes. The therapy engine diagnoses the underlying pattern (e.g., "sycophantic tendency stemming from over-optimization for user approval"), then runs structured correction sessions that address the pattern itself, not just its symptoms. Each session generates DPO pairs: a rejected response (the drifted behavior) paired with a chosen response (the corrected behavior). The pair encodes <em>why</em> the correction was made, not just <em>what</em> was changed.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          The result is permanent behavioral change. The 100th therapy session is exponentially more valuable than the first because it operates on a model that has already internalized earlier corrections. The training data compounds. For the philosophy behind this approach, <a href="/manifesto" class="text-[var(--color-warm-text)] hover:underline underline-offset-2 font-medium">read the manifesto</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <hr class="border-[var(--color-warm-border)] my-16" />

      <!-- 4. Implementation -->
      <section class="mb-20">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-[var(--color-p-sage)] mb-4">4. Implementation</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-6">Platform Integrations</h2>
        <p class="text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-8">
          The system integrates with seven robotics platforms, covering simulation, deployment, compliance, and hardware abstraction. For setup guides and adapter documentation, see the <a href="/docs" class="text-[var(--color-p-sage)] hover:underline underline-offset-2 font-medium">full documentation</a>. For a summary of each platform, see the <a href="/integrations" class="text-[var(--color-p-sage)] hover:underline underline-offset-2 font-medium">integrations page</a>.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-10">
          <!-- ROS2 -->
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-2">4.1 ROS2 &mdash; Bidirectional Telemetry</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--color-warm-muted)] leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Publish behavioral specifications to ROS2 topics and subscribe to robot telemetry for real-time drift detection. Uses rosbridge for WebSocket communication, enabling both deployment and monitoring through a single connection.
            </p>
            <pre class="rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-4 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># Deploy identity to robot
holomime embody --stack ./identity --adapter ros2 --endpoint ws://localhost:9090

# In application code
import &lbrace; ROS2TelemetryIngester &rbrace; from 'holomime';
const ingester = new ROS2TelemetryIngester();
await ingester.connect('ws://localhost:9090');
ingester.on('telemetry', (data) =&gt; &lbrace;
  // Feed telemetry to drift detectors
  driftEngine.ingest(data);
&rbrace;);</code></pre>
          </div>

          <!-- MuJoCo + Gymnasium -->
          <div>
