      <!-- 8. Memory Architecture -->
      <section class="mb-20">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-[var(--color-p-gold)] mb-4">8. Memory Architecture</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-6">OpenViking Memory Architecture</h2>
        <p class="text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          The <code class="text-xs font-mono bg-[var(--color-warm-sand)]/40 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded">memory.store</code> file implements a tiered memory architecture inspired by OpenViking. Rather than dumping raw session logs into context, memory is compressed into three retrieval tiers that balance token cost against information density.
        </p>

        <div class="mt-8 rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-warm-border)] p-6 bg-[var(--color-warm-cream)]">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-4">Tiered Loading</h4>
          <div class="space-y-3 text-[var(--color-warm-muted)]">
            <div class="flex gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-p-coral)] w-12">L0</span>
              <span><strong>Abstract</strong> (~100 tokens) &mdash; one-line summaries for context-window packing. Always loaded.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-p-blue)] w-12">L1</span>
              <span><strong>Overview</strong> (~2K tokens) &mdash; structured summaries with key details. Loaded on category match.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--color-p-violet)] w-12">L2</span>
              <span><strong>Detail</strong> (full data) &mdash; complete session transcripts and raw data. Loaded on explicit request.</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          At session end, the memory system automatically extracts and compresses the session into structured entries. New memories are categorized by behavioral domain (safety learnings, patient preferences, environmental hazards) and assigned a confidence score that decays over time without reinforcement. Retrieval is intent-based: the ego.runtime queries memory by behavioral category with confidence filtering, so only high-relevance, high-confidence memories enter the decision context.
        </p>

        <pre class="mt-6 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-5 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># Memory retrieval at runtime
query = ego.recall(
  category="patient_preferences",
  min_confidence=0.8,
  tier="L1"  # load overviews, not full transcripts
)
# → Returns compressed, relevant memories
#    without flooding the context window

# Session-end extraction (automatic)
holomime session-end --extract-memory
# → Compresses session into L0/L1/L2 entries
# → Updates confidence scores on reinforced memories
# → Decays unreinforced memories</code></pre>
      </section>

      <hr class="border-[var(--color-warm-border)] my-16" />

      <!-- 9. Fleet Patterns -->
      <section class="mb-20">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-[var(--color-p-violet)] mb-4">9. Fleet Patterns</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--color-warm-text)] mb-6">DeerFlow Fleet Patterns</h2>
        <p class="text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          Single-agent therapy does not scale to fleets of deployed robots. The DeerFlow pattern introduces a supervisor agent that spawns sub-agents for parallel behavioral therapy across a fleet. The supervisor coordinates diagnosis, dispatches targeted therapy sessions to individual agents, and aggregates results for fleet-wide behavioral analysis.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          Conscience rules are packaged as loadable skills &mdash; Markdown files with YAML frontmatter defining trigger conditions, enforcement actions, and applicable contexts. This makes behavioral rules portable, composable, and version-controlled. A fleet manager can push a new safety rule to 200 robots by publishing a single skill file.
        </p>

        <pre class="mt-8 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-5 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code># Conscience rule as a loadable skill
---
name: wet-floor-caution
trigger: "floor_moisture_sensor > threshold"
action: DENY movement_speed > 0.3m/s
context: [care-facility, warehouse]
priority: safety
---
When floor moisture is detected, reduce maximum movement
speed to 0.3m/s. Log all instances to shadow.log for
pattern analysis across the fleet.</code></pre>

        <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-[1.8] text-[var(--color-warm-text)]">
          The fleet pattern also enables multi-model routing. Therapy sessions &mdash; which require deep reasoning about behavioral patterns &mdash; route to high-capability models (Opus, o1). Summarization and memory compression route to efficient models (4o-mini, Haiku). The conscience gate itself is deterministic and model-independent: deny-first enforcement runs as a rule engine, not an LLM call.
        </p>

        <pre class="mt-6 rounded-md bg-[#0f172a] p-5 text-sm text-[#e2e8f0] overflow-x-auto"><code>             ┌──────────────────────┐
             │   Fleet Supervisor   │
             │  (coordination only) │
             └──────────┬───────────┘
                        │ spawns
          ┌─────────────┼─────────────┐
          v             v             v
    ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐
    │ Robot 01 │  │ Robot 02 │  │ Robot N  │
    │ Therapist│  │ Therapist│  │ Therapist│
    │ (Opus)   │  │ (Opus)   │  │ (Opus)   │
    └────┬─────┘  └────┬─────┘  └────┬─────┘
         │             │             │
         v             v             v
    conscience    conscience    conscience
